{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569584"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:29:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:29:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22271"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22271","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22271"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.52,0.03,0.18,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15236"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108947"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15236"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2025-07-05T15:17:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-31T14:40:46+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2025-07-16T15:25:48+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-27 18:38:13"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22271"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"13477"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"7912"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91316"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"141"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40277"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40289"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40407"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40670"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43761"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91316"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108947"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for review. She has a medical history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes, and stage 4 chronic kidney disease (CKD) with an estimated glomerular filtration rate of 22 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2. Her medications include perindopril, amlodipine, prazosin, gliclazide, linagliptin and atorvastatin. She mentions increasing back pain over the past six months. She has a family history of osteoporosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECalcium 2.3 mmol/L (2.1-2.6)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPhosphate 1.8 mmol/L (0.8-1.5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EParathyroid hormone 18 pmol/L (1.6-6.9)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E25-hydroxyvitamin D 38 nmol/L (50-150)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAlkaline phosphatase 142 U/L (30-110)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDual-energy X-ray absorptiometry scan shows a T-score of -2.9 at the lumbar spine and -2.7 at the femoral neck. In discussion with the patient\u0027s nephrologist, she is commenced on denosumab, with close monitoring of adverse effects.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following adverse effects is this patient at increased risk of in the context of her chronic kidney disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Atypical femoral fractures","Hypocalcaemia","Hyponatraemia","Hyperkalaemia","Osteonecrosis of the jaw"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has stage 4 CKD and osteoporosis, for which she has been prescribed denosumab. Denosumab is a monoclonal antibody that inhibits RANK ligand, thereby decreasing osteoclast formation and activity, which reduces bone resorption and increases bone mineral density.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypocalcaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is a significant risk in patients with CKD who are treated with denosumab. This patient has several risk factors that predispose her to hypocalcaemia: stage 4 CKD, elevated parathyroid hormone (indicating secondary hyperparathyroidism), low vitamin D levels, and elevated phosphate. In CKD, there is impaired conversion of vitamin D to its active form, leading to decreased intestinal calcium absorption. Additionally, secondary hyperparathyroidism develops as a compensatory mechanism to maintain calcium homeostasis. When denosumab is administered, it rapidly decreases bone resorption, which can precipitate hypocalcaemia, especially in patients with pre-existing mineral metabolism abnormalities like those seen in CKD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtypical femoral fractures\u003C/strong\u003E are a rare complication associated with long-term use of antiresorptive therapies, including denosumab. While this is a potential concern with prolonged therapy, it is not specifically increased by the presence of CKD compared to other adverse effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyponatraemia\u003C/strong\u003E is not a recognised adverse effect of denosumab therapy. While patients with CKD may develop electrolyte abnormalities, hyponatraemia is not specifically associated with denosumab use in the context of CKD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperkalaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is a common electrolyte abnormality in patients with CKD, particularly those on medications like angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitors (perindopril in this case). However, it is not directly related to denosumab therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteonecrosis of the jaw\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare but serious complication associated with antiresorptive therapies, including denosumab. Risk factors include invasive dental procedures, poor oral hygiene, and concurrent use of glucocorticoids. While this is a potential concern with denosumab therapy, the risk is not specifically increased by CKD compared to hypocalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBefore initiating denosumab in patients with CKD, it is recommended to optimise calcium and vitamin D levels and to monitor calcium levels closely after administration. This patient\u0027s vitamin D level is below the reference range, which should be addressed before or concurrently with denosumab therapy to minimise the risk of hypocalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Denosumab can cause hypocalcaemia, particularly in patients with chronic kidney disease due to impaired vitamin D metabolism and secondary hyperparathyroidism.","Patients with chronic kidney disease should have calcium and vitamin D levels optimised before starting denosumab therapy.","Regular monitoring of calcium levels is essential when using denosumab in patients with chronic kidney disease."],"references":["Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) Management in Primary Care (5th edition). Kidney Health Australia. 2024. Available from: https://assets.kidney.org.au/resources/KHA-CKD-Handbook-5th-Ed-July2024.pdf","Yong C. Denosumab-related hypocalcaemia in chronic kidney disease. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2018 Jul 27;47:538\u20139. Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2018/august/denosumab-related-hypocalcaemia-in-chronic-kidney"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91316"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22271"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91316"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-15T09:32:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-15T09:34:29+09:30","number":8,"notes":"Abbreviated chronic kidney disease to CKD after first use throughout the stem and explanation as requested. Reformatted stem to follow proper structure with patient profile, setting, and examination findings.","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-07-15T09:33:35+09:30","plagiarismScore":5.7,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-15236-8.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250929%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250929T145916Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=571049c0615a57c20185859df9077574ff51cb7b96bf5049384ce2f5f6885055"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15236"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108947"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"2888"}},"generation":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisionGenerations","id":"23404"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"73","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/73"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Post-graduate","synonyms":null,"description":"Not suitable for a medical student","position":2,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"